<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="66" type="nomenclatural notes">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Nomenclatural notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="66">
When describing 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. rufipes" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="rufipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">C. rufipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Seubert, MA" editor="Martius, CFP" journalOrPublisher="3, part 1. Leipzig apud Frid. Fleischer, Munich" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" pagination="233 - 270" refId="B29" refString="Seubert, MA, 1855. Commelinaceae. In: Martius, CFP, Eichler, AW, Eds., Flora Brasiliensis, vol. 3, part 1. Leipzig apud Frid. Fleischer, Munich: 233 - 270" title="Commelinaceae." volumeTitle="Flora Brasiliensis, vol." year="1855">Seubert (1855)</bibRefCitation>
only mentions that his new species was based on a Martius specimen, at M. After searching the M collection, we found just two specimens from this collector - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Martius 76</emphasis>
(M0210921) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Martius 77</emphasis>
(M0210920). Since the specimen 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Martius 76</emphasis>
was clearly annotated in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Seubert’s">Seubert's</normalizedToken>
handwriting it is the obvious choice for a lectotype. Nonetheless, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Seubert’s">Seubert's</normalizedToken>
original description makes it clear that all available specimens had few if any flowers, which matches the specimens found by us at M. This has caused great taxonomic problems over the years, with this name being ascribed to a number of different genera (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">i.e. Athyrocarpus</emphasis>
Schltdl., 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="Commelina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelina" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Commelina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Pichon, 1946" authorityName="Pichon" authorityYear="1946" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Commelinopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelinopsis" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Commelinopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Pichon, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hasskarl" authorityYear="1866" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Phaeosphaerion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Phaeosphaerion" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Phaeosphaerion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hassk.), and as either accepted or as a synonym by different authors (Faden &amp; Hunt 1987). Thus, in accordance to the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Code</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill, J" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of Botany" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" refId="B21" refString="McNeill, J, Barrie, FR, Buck, WR, Demoulin, V, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Marhold, K, Prado, J, Prud'Homme Van Reine, WF, Smith, GF, Wiersema, JH, Turland, NJ, 2012. (2012) International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Regnum Vegetabile 154. A.R.G. Gantner Verlag KG, 1-240." title="(2012) International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Regnum Vegetabile 154. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag KG, 1 - 240." year="2012">McNeill et al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
, Art. 9.8), we also designate a well-preserved flowering specimen as an epitype, to avoid further taxonomic and nomenclatural problems.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="66" type="taxonomical notes">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Taxonomical notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="66">
Apart from the obvious difference in indumenta, the leaves of 
<taxonomicName authority="var. rufipes" family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. rufipes subsp. var. var. rufipes" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" rank="variety" species="rufipes" subSpecies="var." variety="rufipes">C. rufipes var. rufipes</taxonomicName>
tend to be thinner (lanceolate to elliptic-lanceolate), with a cuneate base and acute apex, while the leaves of 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. rufipes subsp. var. var. glabrata" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" rank="variety" species="rufipes" subSpecies="var." variety="glabrata">C. rufipes var. glabrata</taxonomicName>
tend to be wider (ovate-elliptic to ovate), with a round to obtuse base and acuminate apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
